

The Order of Events
	1	The Pod Starts (PodInitializing): When you ran k apply -f pod-tem.yml, Kubernetes started the init-contcontainer first. The main Nginx container (main-cont) was blocked from starting until this init container exited successfully (exit code 0).
	2	The until Loop Checks DNS: Inside the init container, the script ran nslookup on your dynamic FQDN address. Because you had already created the service (kubectl create service clusterip my-svc...), CoreDNS instantly resolved my-svc.default.svc.cluster.local to the ClusterIP 10.111.14.207.
	3	Success & Handoff (Running): Since nslookup succeeded on the very first try, the until loop broke immediately, printed "container ran successfully", and exited. Kubernetes saw the init container finish cleanly and immediately spun up your main Nginx container, changing the status from PodInitializing to Running in just 3 seconds.
What would happen if the service didn't exist?
If you hadn't created the service beforehand, your terminal logs would have looked like this:
	1	nslookup would fail (exit code non-zero).
	2	The loop would print: trying to access my-svc but not reachable and so it is pending please create service 
	3	It would sleep for 2 seconds and try again, keeping the Pod stuck in PodInitializing indefinitely until someone ran the kubectl create service command in another terminal.
One Small Warning for Production
While this is a fantastic pattern for ensuring deployment order, busybox's implementation of nslookup can sometimes behave unpredictably with certain DNS search paths if the service drops packets during a rollout.
For a production-grade version of this loop, using nc (netcat) or curl to check for actual port readiness alongside DNS resolution is often more robust:
Bash

until nc -z -w 2 my-svc.$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/namespace).svc.cluster.local 80; do
  echo "Waiting for service port 80..."
  sleep 2
done


