Here is the complete solution and explanation for setting up your multi-container Pod based on the Init Container (Service Dependency) and Readiness Probe design patterns.
Understanding the Architecture
Before looking at the YAML, let's address your note: referring to qsn Port : 8400 but sec created on 80.
	•	The Init Container checks if the Service (eureka-cp-svc) exists via CoreDNS.
	•	The Readiness Probe checks the Application Container directly on port 8400 where the actual InfyTel microservice process is listening inside the container.
	•	Even if an external Kubernetes Service maps to port 80, the probe interacts directly with the container's network namespace on port 8400.
The Complete Pod Manifest (infytel-pod.yaml)
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: infytel-customer-service
  labels:
    app: infytel-customer
spec:
  # 1. Init Container to verify eureka-cp-svc existence
  initContainers:
    - name: verify-eureka-service
      image: busybox:1.36
      command: ["sh", "-c"]
      args:
        - |
          echo "Checking for existence of eureka-cp-svc..."
          NAMESPACE=$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/namespace)
          SVC_URL="eureka-cp-svc.${NAMESPACE}.svc.cluster.local"
          
          until nslookup $SVC_URL; do
            echo "eureka-cp-svc is not reachable yet. Retrying in 2 seconds..."
            sleep 2
          done
          
          echo "eureka-cp-svc is reachable! Init container exiting successfully."

  # 2. Main Application Container
  containers:
    - name: infytel-app-container
      image: nginx:alpine # Replace with your actual InfyTel customer micro-service image
      ports:
        - containerPort: 8400
          name: app-port
      
      # 3. Health Probe Implementation
      readinessProbe:
        tcpSocket:
          port: 8400
        initialDelaySeconds: 5
        periodSeconds: 10
Specification Breakdown
1. Init Container (Service Verification)
	•	Design Pattern: Init Container.
	•	Mechanism: It dynamically determines its namespace from /var/run/secrets/..., structures the FQDN for eureka-cp-svc, and loops nslookup every 2 seconds.
	•	Requirement Fulfilled: "Only if the service is reachable, then proceed to create the actual micro-service container". Since an init container must exit with code 0 before main containers start, the main app is blocked until the DNS record exists.
2. Readiness Probe Config
	•	tcpSocket.port: 8400: Performs a three-way TCP handshake on port 8400. If the port accepts the connection, the check passes.
	•	initialDelaySeconds: 5: Kubernetes waits exactly 5 seconds after the container starts before firing the first probe, giving your application binary a moment to boot up.
	•	periodSeconds: 10: Instructs the kubelet to repeat this check every 10 seconds to ensure the microservice stays healthy.

